      "question": "Why does scaled dot-product attention divide dot products by the square root of the vector dimension?",
      "stem_format": "plain_text",
      "choices_format": "plain_text",
      "choices": [
        "To keep softmax inputs from becoming too large as dimension grows, preserving useful gradients.",
        "To force every query to attend uniformly to all keys.",
        "To remove the need for learned key and value projections.",
        "To make the output sequence shorter than the input sequence."
      ],
      "answer_index": 0,
      "explanation": "Dot products tend to grow in magnitude with dimension. Scaling keeps the values entering softmax in a healthier range, which helps avoid saturated probabilities and weak gradients.",
